 robust and diverse Latin American literary and filmic tradition. The contributors discuss such topics as impairment, trauma, illness and the body, performance, queer theory, subaltern studies, and human rights, while analyzing literature and film from Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Cuba, Mexico, and Peru. They explore these issues through the work of canonical figures Jorge Luis Borges, Gabriel García Márquez, João Guimarães Rosa, and others, as well as less well-known figures, including Mario Bellatin and Miriam Alves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHuman body in literaturexLatin AmericaxCriticism, interpretation, etc. 0aHuman body in literature. 0aMotion picturesxLatin America. 0aMotion pictureszLatin America. 0aPeople with disabilities in literature. 0aPeople with disabilities in motion pictures. 0aSpanish American literaturexHistory and criticism. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Disabilities. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAntebi, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAntebi, Susan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBeth E., Jörgensen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickman-Burnett, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEspinosa, Juan Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarrett, Victoria L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGavioli, Nicola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldstein, Kevin, econ